  "prompt": "Why don't most of the female artistic gymnasts develop hips?",
  "response": "Female artistic gymnasts often have delayed or less pronounced hip development due to several factors:\n\n1. Intense training: Rigorous gymnastics training during critical developmental years can delay puberty and reduce body fat percentage.\n\n2. Low body fat: Gymnasts maintain extremely low body fat levels, which can suppress estrogen production and slow down hormonal changes that typically lead to hip development.\n\n3. High-intensity physical activity: Consistent, high-level training can affect hormonal patterns and potentially delay secondary sexual characteristics.\n\n4. Early training: Many gymnasts begin training at a very young age, which can impact their natural physical development.\n\n5. Genetics and body type: Some gymnasts may naturally have a lean, more linear body type.\n\nIt's important to note that while this is common, it's not universal, and individual experiences can vary. Some gymnasts do develop more typical adult body shapes after retiring from competitive gymnastics.",
